    <main>
        <div class="education-content">
            <!-- Seasonal Lawn Care -->
            <div class="education-section">
                <h2>🌱 Seasonal Lawn Care Guide</h2>
                <p>Your lawn has different needs throughout the year. Follow this seasonal guide to keep your grass healthy and vibrant.</p>
                
                <div class="seasonal-tips">
                    <div class="season">
                        <h3>Spring (March - May)</h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Rake up winter debris</li>
                            <li>Apply pre-emergent weed control</li>
                            <li>Start mowing when grass reaches 3 inches</li>
                            <li>Fertilize with slow-release formula</li>
                            <li>Check irrigation system</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="season">
                        <h4>Summer (June - August)</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Water deeply but infrequently</li>
                            <li>Mow at higher setting (3-4 inches)</li>
                            <li>Apply summer fertilizer</li>
                            <li>Watch for pests and diseases</li>
                            <li>Avoid mowing during drought</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="season">
                        <h4>Fall (September - November)</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Continue mowing until growth stops</li>
                            <li>Apply fall fertilizer</li>
                            <li>Rake leaves regularly</li>
                            <li>Overseed thin areas</li>
                            <li>Winterize irrigation system</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="season">
                        <h4>Winter (December - February)</h4>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Keep off frozen grass</li>
                            <li>Remove heavy snow carefully</li>
                            <li>Plan spring maintenance</li>
                            <li>Service lawn equipment</li>
                            <li>Monitor for winter damage</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Mowing Best Practices -->
            <div class="education-section">
                <h2>✂️ Mowing Best Practices</h2>
                <p>Proper mowing is crucial for lawn health. Follow these guidelines for professional results.</p>
                
                <div class="tip-grid">
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Mowing Height</h4>
                        <p>Keep grass at 3-4 inches tall. Taller grass develops deeper roots and shades out weeds.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>One-Third Rule</h4>
                        <p>Never remove more than one-third of the grass blade length in a single mowing.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Sharp Blades</h4>
                        <p>Sharp mower blades create clean cuts that heal quickly and prevent disease.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Mowing Pattern</h4>
                        <p>Change your mowing direction each time to prevent grass from leaning in one direction.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Dry Grass</h4>
                        <p>Mow when grass is dry to prevent clumping and ensure even cutting.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Leave Clippings</h4>
                        <p>Leave grass clippings on the lawn - they provide natural fertilizer and don't cause thatch.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="warning-box">
                    <h4>⚠️ Common Mowing Mistakes</h4>
                    <p>• Mowing too short (scalping)<br>
                    • Mowing wet grass<br>
                    • Using dull blades<br>
                    • Mowing too infrequently</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Watering Guidelines -->
            <div class="education-section">
                <h2>💧 Watering Guidelines</h2>
                <p>Proper watering is essential for a healthy lawn. Learn when and how much to water.</p>
                
                <div class="tip-grid">
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Watering Schedule</h4>
                        <p>Water deeply 2-3 times per week rather than daily light watering. This encourages deep root growth.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Early Morning Watering</h4>
                        <p>Water between 6-10 AM to minimize evaporation and prevent fungal diseases.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Water Amount</h4>
                        <p>Apply 1-1.5 inches of water per week, including rainfall. Use a rain gauge to measure.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Signs of Under-Watering</h4>
                        <p>Grass blades fold, footprints remain visible, and grass turns bluish-gray.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Signs of Over-Watering</h4>
                        <p>Excessive thatch, fungal growth, and shallow root systems.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Drought Response</h4>
                        <p>During drought, grass may go dormant. This is normal and it will green up when rain returns.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <table class="frequency-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Season</th>
                            <th>Frequency</th>
                            <th>Amount</th>
                            <th>Best Time</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Spring</td>
                            <td>2-3 times/week</td>
