            <!-- Fertilization Guide -->
            <div class="education-section">
                <h2>🌿 Fertilization Guide</h2>
                <p>Proper fertilization provides essential nutrients for healthy grass growth and development.</p>
                
                <div class="tip-grid">
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Soil Testing</h4>
                        <p>Test your soil every 2-3 years to determine nutrient needs and pH levels.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>NPK Ratio</h4>
                        <p>Look for balanced fertilizers (e.g., 16-4-8) with nitrogen for growth, phosphorus for roots, and potassium for health.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Slow-Release Fertilizer</h4>
                        <p>Use slow-release formulas that feed grass gradually over 6-8 weeks.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Application Timing</h4>
                        <p>Fertilize when grass is actively growing, typically spring and fall for cool-season grasses.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Even Application</h4>
                        <p>Use a spreader and apply fertilizer evenly to prevent burning and uneven growth.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Water After Application</h4>
                        <p>Water lightly after fertilizing to activate the nutrients and prevent burning.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="success-box">
                    <h4>✅ Fertilization Schedule</h4>
                    <p><strong>Spring:</strong> Apply when grass starts growing (March-April)<br>
                    <strong>Summer:</strong> Light application if needed (June)<br>
                    <strong>Fall:</strong> Most important application (September-October)<br>
                    <strong>Winter:</strong> No fertilization needed</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Weed Control -->
            <div class="education-section">
                <h2>🌱 Weed Control Strategies</h2>
                <p>Prevent and control weeds with these effective strategies for a weed-free lawn.</p>
                
                <div class="tip-grid">
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Pre-Emergent Herbicides</h4>
                        <p>Apply in early spring before weed seeds germinate to prevent annual weeds.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Post-Emergent Herbicides</h4>
                        <p>Use selective herbicides to kill existing weeds without harming grass.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Manual Removal</h4>
                        <p>Pull weeds by hand when soil is moist, ensuring you remove the entire root system.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Healthy Lawn Prevention</h4>
                        <p>A thick, healthy lawn naturally prevents weeds by crowding them out.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Proper Mowing</h4>
                        <p>Mowing at the correct height prevents weed seeds from getting sunlight to germinate.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Regular Maintenance</h4>
                        <p>Address weed problems early before they spread and become difficult to control.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="warning-box">
                    <h4>⚠️ Weed Control Safety</h4>
                    <p>• Always read and follow herbicide labels<br>
                    • Apply on calm days to prevent drift<br>
                    • Keep children and pets off treated areas<br>
                    • Store herbicides safely out of reach</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Problem Solving -->
            <div class="education-section">
                <h2>🔍 Common Lawn Problems &amp; Solutions</h2>
                <p>Identify and solve common lawn problems before they become serious issues.</p>
                
                <div class="tip-grid">
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Brown Patches</h4>
                        <p>Usually caused by drought, disease, or pests. Check soil moisture and look for signs of disease or insect damage.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Thin Grass</h4>
                        <p>Overseed in fall, improve soil quality, and ensure proper watering and fertilization.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Mushrooms</h4>
                        <p>Indicate excess moisture. Improve drainage and reduce watering frequency.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Thatch Buildup</h4>
                        <p>Remove excess thatch with a dethatcher in early spring or fall.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Compacted Soil</h4>
                        <p>Aerate in spring or fall to improve root growth and water penetration.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tip-card">
                        <h4>Grub Damage</h4>
                        <p>Apply grub control in late spring or early summer to prevent damage.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Professional Help -->
            <div class="education-section">
                <h2>📞 When to Call the Professionals</h2>
                <p>While many lawn care tasks can be done yourself, some situations require professional expertise.</p>
                
                <div class="success-box">
                    <h4>✅ Call Holliday's Lawn &amp; Garden When:</h4>
                    <p>• You need a complete lawn renovation<br>
                    • Severe pest or disease problems persist<br>
                    • You want professional landscape design<br>
                    • Large trees need trimming or removal<br>
                    • You need irrigation system installation<br>
                    • You prefer regular maintenance service</p>
                </div>
                
